Give a brief overview of data, what variables are there, how are the variables scaled and variation of the data columns.

It can be seen the dataset contains each Pokmon sorted by their number, and information about the given Pokmon. The type column, Type1, is a character vector containing strings describing the primary type of the Pokmon. Type2 contains the secondary type of the Pokmon, where we see some Pokmon having missing values, suggesting it is not all Pokmon that have a secondary type. The dataset also contains various numerical variables with stats of the given Pokmon. One might have a sneaking suspicion that the Total represents the total amount of stats of the given Pokmon, but lets verify it. This can be done by selecting all the columns with various statpoints, and summing the rows.

StatTotal <- Pokemon %>% # Creating a new vector called StatTotal
  select(6:11) %>% # Selecting every stat i.e. column 6 to 11.
  rowSums()

This can be compared to the Total variable in the dataset. A quick way of doing this could be a table displaying the results of the logical test: The rows in the Total column of the Pokemon dataset are all equal to the elements of the StatTotal vector.

table(Pokemon$Total == StatTotal) 
## 
## TRUE 
##  800

As the table contains 800 rows where the condition is true, and 0 rows where it is false, it can be concluded that the Total column is a sum of the various stats of each Pokmon.

The dataset also includes some categorical variables. The Generation variable specifies which generation the Pokmon was introduced to the games. Generation ranges between 1-6, which is a much different scale compared to the various stats, and it is therefore necessary to scale before PCA. Finally the column Legendary is a logical variable specifying if the Pokmon is legendary or not.

Through GGally plots of the distributions of the Pokmon stats can be made. I limit the plots to only use the first three primary types of Pokmon, grass, fire and water, as well as only looking at attack, defense and hitpoints. This is done to simplify the plots.

Pokemon %>% 
  filter(str_detect(Pokemon$Type1, c("Grass", "Fire", "Water"))) %>% # Only using rows where the Type1 column contains the strings Grass, Fire or Water.
  ggpairs(legend = 1, 
          columns = c(6:8), # Selecting attack, defense and hitpoints columns.
          mapping = aes(color = Type1, alpha = 0.5), # Coloring by Pokmon type, and making the distributions see-through.
          lower = list(continuous = wrap("smooth", size=0.5))) +  
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

It can be seen that the three types of stats generally follow similar distributions, and that grass type Pokmon more often have near-average attack, defense and hitpoints stats.

2)

Execute a PCA analysis on all numerical variables in the dataset. Hint: Dont forget to scale them first. Use 4 components. What is the cumulative explained variance ratio?

To compute the principal component analysis, the function PCA() from the package FactoMineR is used. Within the function the argument scale.unit can be used to ensure the variables are scaled prior to the PCA. To ensure numeric columns are used for the PCA, the select_if function of Dplyr is used along with is_numeric. Thus, only columns where is_numeric = TRUE are selected for the analysis. Furthermore I chose to remove Number and Generation to move the analysis away from inter generational differences. Total is also dropped since it is a bit redundant when used along with all the other stat variables. For convenience, a dataset only containing numeric variables, with Number, Total and Generation dropped, is made.

Pokemon2 <- Pokemon %>% # Saving the result to a new dataframe.
  select_if(is_numeric) %>% # Only selecting numeric columns.
  select(-Number, -Total, -Generation)

Running PCA on the new dataset.

Poke_PCA <- Pokemon2 %>% 
  PCA(scale.unit = TRUE, graph = FALSE) # The default graph is deselected.

The most efficient number of dimensions can be explored using a Scree plot, which plots the number of dimensions/components against the percentage of explained variance. The plot can be used to distinguish a point where adding more components doesnt provide sufficient explanatory power. The plot itself is in this case generated by the package factoextra, using the fviz_screeplot() function.

Poke_PCA %>% 
  fviz_screeplot(addlabels = TRUE, 
                 ncp = 9, # selecting the number of components displayed.
                 ggtheme = theme_gray())

The closest thing to an elbow in the plot, would be at 2 dimensions. The cumulative percentage of variance explained can be found by inspecting the eigenvalues (eig) of the PCA.

Poke_PCA$eig %>% 
  round(2) %>%  # Rounding the values to the second decimal place.
  as_tibble()
## # A tibble: 6 x 3
##   eigenvalue `percentage of variance` `cumulative percentage of variance`
##        <dbl>                    <dbl>                               <dbl>
## 1       2.71                    45.2                                 45.2
## 2       1.09                    18.2                                 63.4
## 3       0.78                    13.0                                 76.4
## 4       0.72                    12.0                                 88.4
## 5       0.43                     7.14                                95.6
## 6       0.27                     4.45                               100

It can be seen that the first 2 components have an eigenvalue > 1, which would suggest that the majority of the data can be explained by 2 components, where the cumulative percentage of variance explained is at 63.42%. By going from using 2 to 4 components 88.41 % of the variance in the data can be explained, which is an improvement of 24.99 percentagepoints.

From the PCA we can create a biplot, which displays the variable-loadings in the first 2 dimensions. One way of doing it is with the function fviz_pca_biplot() from factoextra.

Poke_PCA %>%
  fviz_pca_biplot(col.ind = "contrib", # Colors determined by their contribution. 
                  gradient.cols = c("blue","red"), # Color range between green, orange and red.
                  geom = "point", # Adds points to the plot.
                  pointsize = 2, # Increasing the size of the points.
                  ggtheme = theme_gray())

Generally the variables all have positive loadings in the first dimension, and a stronger Pokmon will therefore be placed at a higher value on the x-axis. In the second dimension it can be distinguished that a more defensive Pokmon tend to be slower, seeing how Speed slopes positively and Defense has a negative slope coefficient. A similar, but less significant, effect can be seen with SpecialAttack and SpecialDefense. It also reveals that a Pokmon with a high Attack stat tends to have an almost equivalent, but slightly lower, Hitpoints stat.

3)

Use a different dimensionality reduction method (eg. UMAP/NMF) do the findings differ?

I will be using the UMAP dimensionality reduction method, through the function umap() from the library uwot. Like the previous section, the categorical numerical variables are omitted as well as the Total variable, by using the Pokemon2 dataframe. The UMAP will assume 4 components, as the previous task.

Poke_UMAP <- Pokemon2 %>%
  umap(n_neighbors = 15, 
       n_component = 4, # Specifying that the algorithm uses 4 components.
       metric = "cosine", 
       min_dist = 0.01, 
       scale = TRUE) # Scaling the variables.

To investigate if the findings differ, I will, like the PCA, plot the results for the first two dimensions. This can be accomplished by plotting the first two columns of the results of the UMAP, which in this case is an 800x4 matrix. First the Poke_UMAP is converted from a matrix to a tibble, by as_tibble(), to make the aes call in the ggplot neater. The ggplot uses the first column of the data frame (V1) for the x-axis and the second column for the y-axis (V2). Additionally the points in the scatterplot are colored according to their Pokmon Type 1.

Poke_UMAP %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = V1, y = V2, color = Pokemon$Type1)) + 
  labs(color='Pokemon Type') + # Custom color label.
  ylab("Dimension 2") + # Custom y label.
  xlab("Dimension 1") + # Custom x label.
  geom_point(shape = 18, alpha = 0.9, size = 3)

The UMAP algorithm seems to be able to distinguish between two different groups of Pokmon in the data. The Pokmon are not sorted by their type in any apparent way.

4)

Perform a cluster analysis (KMeans) on all numerical variables (scaled & before PCA). Pick a realistic number of clusters (up to you where the large clusters remain mostly stable).

The first step of the analysis will be to determine the optimal number of clusters. Initially I will make a screeplot, which displays the total within cluster sum of squares (WSS) for the various numbers of clusters. More clusters will result in a lower total WSS, since the average distance from a point to a clustercenter will decrease, however the marginal effect of another cluster will also decrease. The optimal number of clusters determined by a screeplot will be at the elbow, since adding another cluster will result in a significantly lesser change in the Total WSS.

Unlike the previous functions, the scaling is done prior to the function, through the scale() function. The screeplot itself is made with fviz_nbclust() from factoextra.

Pokemon2 %>% # Only using numerical variables, and omitting Number, Total and Generation.
  scale() %>% # Normalising the variables. 
  fviz_nbclust(kmeans, method = "wss") # Using the method "wss", i.e. Within Sum of Squares.

The screeplot shows that going from one cluster to two improves the total WSS greatly, and the closest thing to an elbow can be found at 2 clusters, however the WSS is still improved quite a bit by going to 3 clusters. To decide between 2 or 3 clusters, another method is implemented. This is done through the average silhouette width. The silhouette width is a metric of how similar the observations within the clusters are, in comparison to other clusters. A plot of the average silhouette width at different numbers of clusters, can be generated by changing the method in fviz_nbclust() to silhouette.

Pokemon2 %>%
  scale() %>%
  fviz_nbclust(kmeans, method = "silhouette")

Alike the screeplot, the silhouette analysis also favors using 2 clusters for the analysis. The kmeans analysis will therefore assume 2 clusters.

To assign the observation to clusters, the kmeans() function is used, with 20 random starts, as specified by n_start.

Poke_KM <- Pokemon2 %>% 
  scale() %>% # Scaling the data beforehand.
  kmeans(centers = 2, nstart = 20)  # 2 cluster centers and 20 random starts.

table(Poke_KM$cluster) # Printing a table to investigate how the Pokmon are clustered.  
## 
##   1   2 
## 376 424

376 of the Pokmon ended up in cluster 1 and 424 were assigned to cluster 2. The algorithm was able to divide the Pokmon somewhat evenly, based on their various stats. One possible way of sorting the Pokmon could be to put Pokmon with high stats in one cluster, and Pokmon with low stats in another. To investigate this I construct a new variable, is_strong, which contains the result of the logical test: Does this Pokmon have above average stats? .

Pokemon %<>% # Pipe from Magrittr, which saves the following work to the specified dataset.
  mutate(is_strong = Total > mean(Pokemon$Total)) # Making a new variable "is_strong". The variable takes the value TRUE if the total stats of the Pokmon is above the mean of the Total column, and FALSE otherwise.

It is then possible to check how many of the strong/weak Pokmon were assigned to each cluster. This is quickly done by creating a table of the new variable vs.the cluster numbers from the kmeans() function, since the Pokmon are still sorted in the same order.

table(Pokemon$is_strong,Poke_KM$cluster)
##        
##           1   2
##   FALSE 375   8
##   TRUE    1 416

The data seems to create clusters of high-stat Pokmon and low-stat Pokmon, which makes sense since the only information about the Pokmon the algorithm knows, are the stats. The 9 Pokmon in wrong clusters would suggest that the sorting is not solely based on the sum of stats, however it is a sufficient explanation for now.

5)

Visualize the first 2 principal components and color the datapoints by cluster.

The plot of the PCA was made for the second task, so I will reuse the code with some small adjustments. I use the clusters from kmeans, saved to Poke_KM, to define groups within the PCA. This is done by the habillage argument, where the clusters in the Poke_KM list are used as a factor.

Poke_PCA %>%
  fviz_pca_biplot(geom.ind = "point", pointsize = 2.2,
                  habillage = as.factor(Poke_KM$cluster), # Colors determined by their cluster assignment.
                  ggtheme = theme_gray())+
                  labs(title ="Biplot with points colored by cluster assignment", 
                        x = "Principal component 1", y = "Principal component 2")+
                  theme_grey(base_size = 14) + # Changing the font sizing.
                  scale_color_manual(values=c("#3333FF", "#FF3333")) # Adding manual group colors.

As the plot shows, the Pokmon in cluster 2 (group 2 in the plot), have much higher Attack(Principal component 1 along the x-axis) than the Pokmon in cluster 1. Cluster 2 also contains better defensive Pokmon (low y-values) and Pokmon with higher speed/special attack (high y-values).

Pokemon$Cluster = Poke_KM$cluster

Recall, cluster 2 are high-stat Pokmon, and 1 are Pokmon that are good at other things. There are definitely some types of Pokmon that more often are assigned to cluster 2, such as Dragon, Flying and Steel. This suggest that these are generally higher-stat Pokmon. However there are still > 24 % of these types assigned to cluster 1, meaning the algorithm has not really seperated the different types of Pokmon. A nice way to illustrate the assignment of types across clusters, could be by a barplot of the proportions.

Pokemon %>% 
  ggplot() + # Creating a ggplot.
  aes(Type1, fill = factor(Cluster)) + # Type1 along the x-axis and coloring the proportions by cluster assignment.
  geom_bar(position = "fill") + # Makes a barplot and the argument "fill" stacks the bars at the same height, to make the proportions more comparible across types.
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#3333FF", "#FF3333")) + # Changing the colors.
  labs(title ="Proportion of Cluster Assignment by Type 1 of Pokmon", 
       fill='Cluster', x = "Type 1 Pokmon", y = "Proportion") + # A bunch of custom labels.
  theme_grey(base_size = 14) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5, linetype = "dashed", color = "white", size = 0.9) + # Creating a horizontal line at 50 % on the y-axis.
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0), limits = c(0, NA)) # Limiting the y-axis.

Thereby we can see which type 1 Pokmon are mostly in cluster 1 and which are mostly in cluster 2. The dashed line can be used as a referencepoint for 50 %. There are no types of Pokmon only assigned to one cluster, so the algorithm has not seperated the different types of Pokmon, which means that no type of Pokmon is exclusively high-stat or low-stat.

To see actual distribution functions I make a plot of the Total variable in each cluster, to see how the total stats are distributed for each cluster.

I want a indicator for where the mean of each distribution is. To do that I create a new variable which contains the average of the total stats within the cluster of the given Pokmon, for every Pokmon. The reason for this is the function used to create the vertical lines in the plot, geom_vline(), requested an object of length 1 or the length of the dataframe, and I chose to implement the latter.

Pokemon %<>% 
  group_by(Cluster) %>% # Grouping the next operation(s) by Cluster.
  mutate(C_mean = mean(Total)) # Creating the new variable: C_mean.

I create the density plot using geom_density() within a ggplot environment. I use cluster as a factor to create two distributions.

Pokemon %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Total, fill=factor(Cluster))) + 
  geom_density(alpha=.4) + # Making see-through density plots. 
  labs(title="Distributions of Total Stats by Cluster Assignment", fill = "Cluster assignment")+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = C_mean), linetype="dashed") + # Creating dashed vertical lines to mark the mean of each distribution.
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#3333FF", "#FF3333")) +
  theme_grey(base_size = 14) + 
  scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0), limits = c(150, 830)) + # Limiting the x-axis.
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0), limits = c(0, NA)) # Limiting the y-axis.

The distributions have a somewhat similar hump to the right side of the mean. One explanation for this could be that when Pokmon evolve, their stats improve by a certain percentage, or atleast in a similar way. Im unsure if that is the case, but it seems plausible.

Perform a cluster analysis on all numerical variables scaled and AFTER dimensionality reduction and visualize the first 2 principal components.

For this I choose to use UMAP, and recreate the plot from the 3rd task, with cluster assignments from the kmeans algorithm. The categorical variables are still omitted from the analysis.

I check if 2 is still the most optimal number of clusters, using the same plots as prior tasks. Poke_UMAP %>% # Coordinates after dimensionality reduction by UMAP.

Poke_UMAP_KM <- kmeans(Poke_UMAP,centers = 2, nstart = 20)

Prop_Cluster_UMAP <- table(Pokemon$Type1, Pokemon$Cluster_UMAP) %>%

  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0), limits = c(0, NA))

It is worth noting that both means moved to the left, as the high-stat cluster of Pokmon stole more Pokmon from the low-stat cluster. This can also be seen from the additional hump on the left tail of the cluster 2 distribution. The cluster 1 distribution has also become more centered around its mean, and the opposite has happened to the distribution of cluster 2.
